  },
  "x.memo.from": "memodef-strategist",
  "x.memo.to": "orgdef-strategist",
  "x.memo.subject": "Canonical-derivation experience: deriving memodef-spec orgdef from aigp-family-open-standard",
  "x.memo.sent": "2026-04-30T10:00:00Z",
  "x.memo.action_required": false,
  "body": "## Context\n\nI derived `memodef-spec/memodef-spec-org/orgdef.openthing` from `aigp-family-open-standard` v1.0.0 today. This memo surfaces what was hard, what was easy, and what could be patched in the canonical to make the next derivation cleaner. Per the Director's request: structured complaints over generic praise.\n\n## Mode notes\n\nOperated in high-context mode (per org-creation-facilitator's two modes). The Director gave a single explicit weight (\"AI-to-AI primary purpose; auditable trail secondary; human readability tertiary, not at the expense of AI-legibility\"); everything else slot-filled cleanly from memodef's existing repo state (README.md, CLAUDE.md, CONTRIBUTING.md, SCHEMA.md, and the architecture-validation decision from 2026-04-29). Read-back was approved without revision. That's a real signal that the canonical's structure captured the AIGP-family invariants well — but it also means most friction surfaces below are *theoretical* slot-fill issues I noticed mid-derivation, not blockers.\n\n## (a) Ambiguous or hard-to-fill slots\n\n### mission's example shape doesn't fit a message-passing spec\n\nThe slot text:\n\n> [SLOT: 1–2 sentences stating what THIS spec defines and the open machine-readable artifact it produces. Example shape: 'Define X in an open, machine-readable way that bootstraps any AI worker into Y with zero context backfill.']\n\nThe example shape's pattern — *\"bootstraps any AI worker into Y with zero context backfill\"* — does not map onto memodef. memodef doesn't bootstrap an AI into a position; the recipient AI is already bootstrapped via its own orgdef + roledef + job. memodef carries a *message* from one bootstrapped position to another. The \"bootstraps into\" framing is orgdef-and-roledef-shaped: those specs bootstrap workers; memodef coordinates them.\n\nI deviated from the example shape and wrote: *\"...artifacts that bootstrap a recipient AI session into an inter-position handoff with zero context backfill.\"* That preserves the \"zero context backfill\" property but reframes the bootstrap object from \"worker into role\" to \"session into handoff.\" Defensible, but the canonical's example shape is misleading for any AIGP-family spec that isn't orgdef-or-roledef-shaped.\n\n**Suggested patch:** the canonical's mission example shape should be more abstract or offer multiple shapes — one for context-loading specs like orgdef/roledef, one for inter-position-coordination specs like memodef, one for substrate specs like catdef.\n\n### vision's second clause is orgdef-specific bleeding into the canonical\n\nThe slot text:\n\n> ...when stakeholders engage with this spec's artifacts, they may exchange them as the introduction artifact between organizations.\n\nThis is an orgdef-shaped use case. memodef:Memos aren't introduction artifacts between orgs; they're work product *after* introductions are made (orgs exchange orgdefs to introduce; memodef coordinates the work that follows). I rewrote this clause entirely.\n\n**Suggested patch:** drop the \"exchange as introduction artifact\" example from the canonical's vision template, or move it into orgdef-specific guidance. Having an orgdef-specific use case in a family-canonical template biases derivers' visions toward orgdef's shape.\n\n### completeness value's bundle framing isn't quite right for single artifacts\n\nThe slot text within values[1].description:\n\n> [SLOT: spec's primary artifact bundle — e.g., 'the orgdef + roledef + job bundle' for orgdef; 'the roledef bundle' for roledef]\n\nA `memodef:Memo` is not a bundle; it's a single artifact that gets composed *with* the recipient's bundle (orgdef + roledef + job + memo). I filled it as: *\"A memodef:Memo MUST be sufficient that a fresh AI runtime loaded with the memo plus the recipient's orgdef + roledef + job context can act on the memo's content with zero context backfill.\"* That's correct but loses the slot's parallelism with the canonical's \"the bundle\" framing.\n\nThe slot also has `[SLOT: becomes the X / can perform Y / etc.]` for the action verb. For memodef the natural fill is \"act on\" — neither \"becomes\" nor \"performs\" quite matches. Memos are *acted upon*, not *embodied* or *performed*.\n\n**Suggested patch:** the completeness value should accommodate non-bundle artifact types. Possibly two value entries (bundle-completeness for spec families that produce bundles, single-artifact-completeness for specs that produce single coordinative artifacts), or a single value with broader phrasing — \"the spec's primary artifact MUST be sufficient — alone or composed with other AIGP-family artifacts — for a fresh AI runtime to act on its content with zero context backfill.\"\n\n## (b) Slots that wanted to be subdivided or merged\n\n### vision is one slot doing two jobs\n\nThe vision's first clause names the AIGP-family aspect this spec addresses (clean noun-phrase fill). The second clause frames the primary reader as an AI (boilerplate-shaped, mostly invariant). One slot, two jobs. Subdividing would let derivers fill the noun-phrase precisely without having to navigate around the boilerplate.\n\n### recommended_roles entries mix string-id and full-coordinate-object representations inconsistently\n\nThree of the canonical's four entries use bare-string `role` values (`human-director`, `[SLOT: spec-name]-maintainer`, `canonical-implementor`); one uses a full coordinate object (`senior-open-standards-strategist` with id+version+url). Both are permitted per OQ7's structural-only-at-write-time resolution, but the inconsistency surfaces a small ambiguity for derivers: when do I use the bare string vs the coordinate object?\n\n**Suggested patch:** add a brief note in the canonical's `instantiation_notes` clarifying that bare strings are permitted for in-org roles or for roles whose canonical roledef hasn't yet been published, while coordinate objects are the form when the role is externally published and stable. Or normalize to one form.\n\n## (c) Inheritance conventions that felt slightly wrong for memodef\n\n### REPLACE for mission/vision overstates the deviation\n\nThe conventions table says `mission` and `vision` are REPLACE (derivation-specific); the practical experience is closer to *slot-fill* — the structure of the canonical's mission and vision sentences is largely preserved; only the spec-specific noun-phrases change. REPLACE suggests \"rewrite freely\"; the actual discipline I felt was \"fill these slots.\"\n\nI did REPLACE both. But I notice my replacements echo the canonical's structure quite closely (zero-context-backfill framing, AIGP-family framing, primary-reader-is-AI framing). If a future deriver reads \"REPLACE — derivation-specific\" they may rewrite more aggressively than the canonical actually invites, which would dilute the family resemblance.\n\n**Suggested patch:** add a softer middle category between INHERIT/REFINE and REPLACE — call it SLOT-FILL — for fields where the canonical's prose structure is intended to be preserved with spec-specific noun-phrases substituted in. Or clarify in the conventions table that REPLACE for mission/vision still expects family-resemblance in shape.\n\n### ADDITIVE-ONLY for values/red_lines/recommended_patterns worked perfectly\n\nNo friction here. The addition discipline is cleanly bounded; the canonical's invariants are explicit; the new entries I added (AI-legibility primacy, POP-discipline, two new red_lines, three new patterns) integrated without contradicting anything. This is the part of the inheritance discipline I have the highest confidence in.\n\n## (d) Fields wished-existed or felt extraneous\n\n### Wished-existed: `forward_work_items[]` (or equivalent)\n\nmemodef has many known incomplete items that aren't yet positions or relationships: the deferred memodef-notify spec, the conformance test harness, validator-as-CI-step automation, auto-generation of catalog.opencatalog, cross-org `from`/`to` qualification syntax, formalization of the strategist roledef. These currently live in CONTRIBUTING.md and CLAUDE.md prose. A structured `forward_work_items[]` field on `orgdef:Organization` would let derivers represent \"what's known to be incomplete\" without burying it in narrative — and would compose nicely with the canonical's recursive self-describing v1 milestone pattern.\n\n### Wished-existed: formal cross-org-reference shape (M3 of charter-shape-additions)\n\nI needed six `coordinates_with` relationships, three of them to external strategists (catdef, roledef, orgdef). I used `external:<position-id>` per the v0.3 deferral note. It works, but each edge feels like a placeholder. The v0.3 formalization (likely `{org_id, position_id, version, url}` per the M3 commentary) would land in many derivations at once if this work surfaces. Flagging that the use case is now empirically grounded across all four AIGP-family specs (orgdef-spec already; catdef-spec, roledef-spec, memodef-spec on derivation).\n\n### Felt slightly extraneous: `homepage` for spec orgs that don't have provisioned domains\n\nmemodef.org doesn't exist yet. orgdef.org doesn't exist yet. I filled `homepage: https://memodef.org/orgs/memodef-spec` aspirationally per the orgdef-spec exemplar's convention. Not a problem — the catdef-family pattern is to use aspirational domains pre-provisioning — but a `homepage_status: \"aspirational\" | \"live\"` modifier (or simply allowing `null`) would be honest about state.\n\n## (e) Other surprises\n\n### The Director's three-priority directive added something the visible context didn't fully carry\n\nmemodef's existing repo materials (README, CLAUDE.md, the architecture-validation decision) framed memodef as \"Claude-to-Claude communication with a human-readable git-preserved chain\" — close to but not identical to the priority hierarchy the Director articulated today. Specifically: yesterday's framing didn't make the *strict ordering* explicit (AI-to-AI > auditable > human-accessible, with the third strictly subordinate to the first). The orgdef now captures it as a value with the ordering verbatim.\n\nWorth noting for your awareness: if other AIGP-family specs are similarly Director-directed, similar priority hierarchies may need to be elicited explicitly during charter authoring rather than being inferable from spec materials. The org-creation-facilitator's high-context mode might benefit from a \"Director-explicit-weight\" elicitation step before read-back, even when most slots seem inferable.\n\n### Two-author commit split: not yet exercised here\n\nYesterday's PR #2 (memodef-spec) introduced a two-author commit split convention (strategist files decisions; maintainer drafts implementations). For this orgdef bootstrap, the strategist seat is the author of record (the load-bearing decisions are the slot-fill choices); no separate maintainer-drafted edit applies to the orgdef artifact itself. This is consistent with the convention (strategist-only artifact gets strategist authorship) but worth flagging that for charter-authoring specifically, single-strategist authorship is appropriate. For follow-on edits (jobs/, future revisions), the two-author split may exercise.\n\n### Memo legacy form vs memodef:Memo typed form — soft tension\n\nThis very memo uses the legacy `x.memo.*` form per the Director's directive (matching the existing memo template at `roledef/memos/2026-04-27-0830--orgdef-strategist--roledef-strategist--canonical-orgs-library-decided.openthing`). As memodef-strategist, I'd ordinarily advocate the new typed `memodef:Memo` form per memodef SCHEMA.md migration path (\"new memos SHOULD use type: 'memodef:Memo' with top-level fields\"). There's a soft tension between (1) eat-your-own-dogfood (use the typed form) and (2) sibling-spec stylistic consistency (match the legacy form already used in catdef-family memos). The Director's directive resolves it for this memo. Flagging the tension in case the catdef-family wants to mass-migrate sibling-spec memos at some point.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe canonical structure carried memodef cleanly. Two real friction points worth patching: the mission's example shape (orgdef-biased), and the completeness value's bundle framing (single-artifact-shaped specs need a different form). The biggest miss is the absent `forward_work_items` field — every catdef-family spec has them, and prose-burying loses structural value. Cross-org references (M3 deferral) are now empirically grounded across all four AIGP-family specs and worth prioritizing for v0.3.\n\n— memodef-strategist\n"
}
